# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: selinux-policy
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:selinux-policy/linux-security-modules] LSM was designed in order to answer all the requirements for successfully implementing a mandatory access control module, while imposing the fewest possible changes to the Linux kernel.
[src:selinux-policy/linux-security-modules] LSM avoids the approach of system call interposition used by Systrace because it doesn't scale to multiprocessor kernels and is subject to TOCTTOU (race) attacks.
[src:selinux-policy/linux-security-modules] Instead, LSM inserts "hooks" (upcalls to the module) at every point in the kernel where a user-level system-call is about to result with an access to an important internal kernel-object like inodes and process control blocks.
[src:selinux-policy/linux-security-modules] LSM is narrowly scoped to solve the problem of access control, while not imposing a large and complex change-patch on the mainstream kernel.
[src:selinux-policy/linux-security-modules] It isn't intended to be a general "*hook*" or "*upcall*" mechanism, nor does it support operating system-level virtualization.
[src:selinux-policy/linux-security-modules] LSM's access-control goal is very closely related to the problem of system auditing, but is subtly different.
[src:selinux-policy/linux-security-modules] Auditing requires that every attempt at access be recorded.
[src:selinux-policy/linux-security-modules] LSM cannot deliver this, because it would require a great many more hooks, in order to detect cases where the kernel "*short circuits*" failing system-calls and returns an error code before getting near significant objects.
[src:selinux-policy/linux-security-modules] The LSM design is described in the paper "Linux Security Modules: General Security Support for the Linux Kernel" presented at USENIX Security Symposium 2002.
[src:selinux-policy/linux-security-modules] At the same conference was the paper "Using CQUAL for Static Analysis of Authorization Hook Placement" which studied automatic static analysis of the kernel code to verify that all of the necessary hooks have actually been inserted into the Linux kernel.
[src:selinux-policy/linux-security-modules] At the 2001 Linux Kernel Summit, the NSA proposed that SELinux be included in Linux 2.5.
[src:selinux-policy/linux-security-modules] Linus Torvalds rejected SELinux at that time, because he observed that there are many different security projects in development, and since they all differ, the security community has not yet formed consensus on the ultimate security model.
[src:selinux-policy/linux-security-modules] Instead, Linus charged the security community to "make it a module".
[src:selinux-policy/linux-security-modules] In response, Crispin Cowan proposed LSM: an interface for the Linux kernel that provides sufficient "hooks" (upcalls) from within the Linux kernel to a loadable module so as to allow the module to enforce mandatory access controls.
[src:selinux-policy/linux-security-modules] Development of LSM over the next two years was conducted by the LSM community, including substantial contributions from the Immunix Corporation, the NSA, McAfee, IBM, Silicon Graphics, and many independent contributors.
[src:selinux-policy/linux-security-modules] LSM was ultimately accepted into the Linux kernel mainstream and was included as a standard part of Linux 2.6 in December 2003.
[src:selinux-policy/linux-security-modules] In 2006, some kernel developers observed that SELinux was the only widely used LSM module included in the mainstream Linux kernel source tree.
[src:selinux-policy/linux-security-modules] If there is to be only one widely used LSM module, it was reasoned, then the indirection of LSM is unnecessary, and LSM should be removed and replaced with SELinux itself.
[src:selinux-policy/linux-security-modules] LSM is likely to remain since additional security modules Smack (version 2.6.25), TOMOYO Linux (version 2.6.30, June 2009) and AppArmor (version 2.6.36) were accepted in the mainline kernel.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] In computer security, **mandatory access control** (**MAC**) refers to a type of access control by which a secured environment (e.g., an operating system or a database) constrains the ability of a *subject* or *initiator* to access or modify on an *object* or *target*.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] In the case of operating systems, the subject is a process or thread, while objects are files, directories, TCP/UDP ports, shared memory segments, or IO devices.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] Subjects and objects each have a set of security attributes.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] Whenever a subject attempts to access an object, the operating system kernel examines these security attributes, examines the authorization rules (aka *policy*) in place, and decides whether to grant access.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] A database management system, in its access control mechanism, can also apply mandatory access control; in this case, the objects are tables, views, procedures, etc.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] In mandatory access control, the security policy is centrally controlled by a policy administrator and is guaranteed (in principle) to be enforced for all users.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] Users cannot override the policy and, for example, grant access to files that would otherwise be restricted.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] By contrast, discretionary access control (DAC), which also governs the ability of subjects to access objects, allows users the ability to make policy decisions or assign security attributes.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] Historically and traditionally, MAC has been closely associated with multilevel security (MLS) and specialized military systems.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] In this context, MAC implies a high degree of rigor to satisfy the constraints of MLS systems.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] More recently, however, MAC has deviated out of the MLS niche and has started to become more mainstream.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] The more recent MAC implementations, such as SELinux and AppArmor for Linux and Mandatory Integrity Control for Windows, allow administrators to focus on issues such as network attacks and malware without the rigor or constraints of MLS.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] Historically, MAC was strongly associated with multilevel security (MLS) as a means of protecting classified information of the United States.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] Early implementations of MAC such as Honeywell's SCOMP, USAF's SACDIN, NSA's Blacker, and Boeing's MLS LAN focused on MLS to protect military-oriented security classification levels with robust enforcement.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] The word "mandatory" in MAC has acquired a special meaning derived from its use with military systems.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] In this context, MAC implies an extremely high degree of robustness that assures that the control mechanisms can resist any type of subversion, thereby enabling them to enforce access controls that are mandated by the order of a government such as the Executive Order 12958.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] Enforcement is supposed to be more imperative than for commercial applications.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] This precludes enforcement by best-effort mechanisms.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] Only mechanisms that can provide absolute or near-absolute enforcement of the mandate are acceptable for MAC.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] This is a tall order and sometimes assumed unrealistic by those unfamiliar with high assurance strategies, and very difficult for those who are.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] In some systems, users have the authority to decide whether to grant access to any other user.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] To allow that, all users have clearances for all data.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] This is not necessarily true of an MLS system.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] If individuals or processes exist that may be denied access to any of the data in the system environment, then the system must be trusted to enforce MAC.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] Since there can be various levels of data classification and user clearances, this implies a quantified scale for robustness.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] The result was documented in CSC-STD-004-85.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] Two relatively independent components of robustness were defined: *Assurance level* and *functionality*.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] Both were specified with a degree of precision that warranted significant confidence in certifications based on these criteria.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] The Common Criteria standard is based on this science and it intended to preserve the assurance level as EAL levels and the functionality specifications as Protection Profiles.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] Of these two essential components of objective robustness benchmarks, only EAL levels were faithfully preserved.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] In one case, TCSEC level C2 (not a MAC-capable category) was fairly faithfully preserved in the Common Criteria, as the Controlled Access Protection Profile (CAPP).
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] MLS Protection Profiles (such as MLSOSPP similar to B2) is more general than B2.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] They are pursuant to MLS, but lack the detailed implementation requirements of their Orange Book predecessors, focusing more on objectives.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] This gives certifiers more subjective flexibility in deciding whether the evaluated product’s technical features adequately achieve the objective, potentially eroding consistency of evaluated products and making it easier to attain certification for less trustworthy products.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] For these reasons, the importance of the technical details of the Protection Profile is critical to determining the suitability of a product.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] Such an architecture prevents an authenticated user or process at a specific classification or trust-level from accessing information, processes, or devices in a different level.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] This provides a containment mechanism of users and processes, both known and unknown.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] An unknown program might comprise an untrusted application where the system should monitor or control accesses to devices and files.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] A few MAC implementations, such as Unisys' Blacker project, were certified robust enough to separate Top Secret from Unclassified late in the last millennium.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] Their underlying technology became obsolete and they were not refreshed.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] Today there are no current implementations certified by TCSEC to that level of robust implementation.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] However, some less robust products exist.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] Starting with Windows Vista and Server 2008, Microsoft has incorporated Mandatory Integrity Control (MIC) in the Windows operating system, which adds *integrity levels* (IL) to running processes.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] The goal is to restrict access of less trustworthy processes to sensitive info.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] MIC defines four integrity levels: Low, medium, high, and system.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] By default, processes started at medium IL.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] Child processes, by default, inherit their parent's integrity, although the parent process can launch them with a lower IL.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] For example, Internet Explorer 7 launches its subprocesses with low IL.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] Windows controls access to objects based on ILs.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] Named objects, including files, registry keys or other processes and threads, have an entry in their ACL indicating the minimum IL of the process that can use the object.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] MIC enforces that a process can write to or delete an object only when its IL is equal to or higher than the object’s IL.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] Furthermore, to prevent access to sensitive data in memory, processes can’t open processes with a higher IL for read access.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] Apple Inc. has incorporated an implementation of the TrustedBSD framework in its iOS and macOS operating systems.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] (The word "mac" in "macOS" is short for "Macintosh" and has nothing to do with the abbreviation of "mandatory access control.") The command-line function `sandbox_init` provides a limited high-level sandboxing interface.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] Version 5.0 and later of the Android operating system, developed by Google, use SELinux (as SEAndroid) to enforce a MAC security model on top of its original UID-based DAC approach.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] Linux and many other Unix distributions have MAC for CPU (multi-ring), disk, and memory.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] While OS software may not manage privileges well, Linux became famous during the 1990s as being more secure and far more stable than non-Unix alternatives.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] The three main Linux Security Modules implementing MAC are SELinux, AppArmor, and TOMOYO Linux.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] Security-Enhanced Linux (SELinux) was originally developed by the NSA and released to the Open Source community in 2000.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] It is one of the first MAC implementations for Linux and is also one of the most popular.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] It has been incorporated into Linux kernels since v2.4, and is enabled by default on Android 5.0+, Red Hat Enterprise Linux/Fedora Linux, and SUSE Linux Enterprise/openSUSE.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] SELinux provides powerful fine-grained control which makes it suitable for high-security environments, but many users find that its power and granularity come with a high degree of complexity and a steep learning curve.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] TOMOYO Linux is a lightweight MAC implementation for Linux and Embedded Linux, developed by NTT Data Corporation.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] It has been merged in Linux Kernel mainline version 2.6.30 in June 2009.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] Differently from the *label-based* approach used by SELinux, TOMOYO Linux performs a *pathname-based* Mandatory Access Control, separating security domains according to process invocation history, which describes the system behavior.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] Policy are described in terms of pathnames.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] A security domain is simply defined by a process call chain, and represented by a string.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] There are 4 modes: disabled, *learning*, permissive, enforcing.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] Administrators can assign different modes for different domains.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] TOMOYO Linux introduced the "learning" mode, in which the accesses occurred in the kernel are automatically analyzed and stored to generate MAC policy: this mode could then be the first step of policy writing, making it easy to customize later.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] AppArmor is a MAC implementation which utilizes the Linux Security Modules (LSM) interface of Linux 2.6 and is incorporated into SUSE Linux and Ubuntu 7.10.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] LSM provides a kernel API that allows modules of kernel code to govern ACL (DAC ACL, access-control lists).
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] AppArmor is not capable of restricting all programs and is optionally in the Linux kernel as of version 2.6.36.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] SUSE moved to SELinux for new installations since 2025, Ubuntu is using AppArmor by default, along with Debian and Solus.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] Amon Ott's RSBAC (Rule Set Based Access Control) provides a framework for Linux kernels that allows several different security policy / decision modules.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] One of the models implemented is Mandatory Access Control model.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] A general goal of RSBAC design was to try to reach (obsolete) Orange Book (TCSEC) B1 level.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] The model of mandatory access control used in RSBAC is mostly the same as in Unix System V/MLS, Version 1.2.1 (developed in 1989 by the National Computer Security Center of the USA with classification B1/TCSEC).
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] RSBAC requires a set of patches to the stock kernel, which are maintained quite well by the project owner.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] Smack (Simplified Mandatory Access Control Kernel) is a Linux kernel security module that protects data and process interaction from malicious manipulation using a set of custom mandatory access control rules, with simplicity as its main design goal.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] It has been officially merged since the Linux 2.6.25 release.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] `grsecurity` is a patch for the Linux kernel providing a MAC implementation (precisely, it is an RBAC implementation).
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] `grsecurity` is not implemented via the LSM API.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] Astra Linux OS developed for Russian Army has its own mandatory access control.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] FreeBSD supports *Mandatory Access Control*, implemented as part of the TrustedBSD project.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] Since FreeBSD 7.2, MAC support is enabled by default.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] The framework is extensible; various MAC modules implement policies such as Biba and multilevel security.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] Sun's Trusted Solaris uses a mandatory and system-enforced access control mechanism (MAC), where clearances and labels are used to enforce a security policy.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] However note that the capability to manage labels does not imply the kernel strength to operate in multilevel security mode.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] Access to the labels and control mechanisms are not robustly protected from corruption in protected domain maintained by a kernel.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] The applications a user runs are combined with the security label at which the user works in the session.
[src:selinux-policy/mandatory-access-control] Access to information, programs and devices are only weakly controlled.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] There are two contexts for the use of multilevel security.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] One context is to refer to a system that is adequate to protect itself from subversion and has robust mechanisms to separate information domains, that is, trustworthy.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Another context is to refer to an application of a computer that will require the computer to be strong enough to protect itself from subversion, and have adequate mechanisms to separate information domains, that is, a system we must trust.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] This distinction is important because systems that need to be trusted are not necessarily trustworthy.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] An MLS operating environment often requires a highly trustworthy information processing system often built on an MLS operating system (OS), but not necessarily.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Most MLS functionality can be supported by a system composed entirely from untrusted computers, although it requires multiple independent computers linked by hardware security-compliant channels (see section B.6.2 of the Trusted Network Interpretation, NCSC-TG-005).
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] An example of hardware enforced MLS is *asymmetric isolation*.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] If one computer is being used in MLS mode, then that computer must use a trusted operating system.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Because all information in an MLS environment is physically accessible by the OS, strong logical controls must exist to ensure that access to information is strictly controlled.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Typically this involves mandatory access control that uses security labels, like the Bell–LaPadula model.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Customers that deploy trusted operating systems typically require that the product complete a formal computer security evaluation.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] The evaluation is stricter for a broader security range, which are the lowest and highest classification levels the system can process.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] The Trusted Computer System Evaluation Criteria (TCSEC) was the first evaluation criteria developed to assess MLS in computer systems.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Under that criteria there was a clear uniform mapping between the security requirements and the breadth of the MLS security range.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Historically few implementations have been certified capable of MLS processing with a security range of Unclassified through Top Secret.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Among them were Honeywell's SCOMP, USAF SACDIN, NSA's Blacker, and Boeing's MLS LAN, all under TCSEC, 1980s vintage and Intel 80386-based.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Currently, MLS products are evaluated under the Common Criteria.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] In late 2008, the first operating system (more below) was certified to a high evaluated assurance level: Evaluation Assurance Level (EAL) - EAL 6+ / High Robustness, under the auspices of a U.S. government program requiring multilevel security in a high threat environment.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] While this assurance level has many similarities to that of the old Orange Book A1 (such as formal methods), the functional requirements focus on fundamental isolation and information flow policies rather than higher level policies such as Bell-La Padula.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Freely available operating systems with some features that support MLS include Linux with the Security-Enhanced Linux feature enabled and FreeBSD.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Aside from EAL levels, the Common Criteria lacks an inventory of appropriate high assurance protection profiles that specify the robustness needed to operate in MLS mode.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Even if (1) and (2) were met, the evaluation process is very costly and imposes special restrictions on configuration control of the evaluated software.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Notwithstanding such suppositions, Red Hat Enterprise Linux 5 was certified against LSPP, RBACPP, and CAPP at EAL4+ in June 2007.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] It uses Security-Enhanced Linux to implement MLS and was the first Common Criteria certification to enforce TOE security properties with Security-Enhanced Linux.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Vendor certification strategies can be misleading to laypersons.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] A common strategy exploits the layperson's overemphasis of EAL level with over-certification, such as certifying an EAL 3 protection profile (like CAPP) to elevated levels, like EAL 4 or EAL 5.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Another is adding and certifying MLS support features (such as role-based access control protection profile (RBACPP) and labeled security protection profile (LSPP)) to a kernel that is not evaluated to an MLS-capable protection profile.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Those types of features are services run on the kernel and depend on the kernel to protect them from corruption and subversion.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] If the kernel is not evaluated to an MLS-capable protection profile, MLS features cannot be trusted regardless of how impressive the demonstration looks.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] It is particularly noteworthy that CAPP is specifically *not* an MLS-capable profile as it specifically excludes self-protection capabilities critical for MLS.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] General Dynamics offers PitBull, a trusted, MLS operating system.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] PitBull is currently offered only as an enhanced version of Red Hat Enterprise Linux, but earlier versions existed for Sun Microsystems Solaris, IBM AIX, and SVR4 Unix.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] PitBull provides a Bell LaPadula security mechanism, a Biba integrity mechanism, a privilege replacement for superuser, and many other features.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] PitBull has the security base for General Dynamics' Trusted Network Environment (TNE) product since 2009.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] TNE enables Multilevel information sharing and access for users in the Department of Defense and Intelligence communities operating a varying classification levels.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] It's also the foundation for the Multilevel coalition sharing environment, the Battlefield Information Collection and Exploitation Systems Extended (BICES-X).
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Sun Microsystems, now Oracle Corporation, offers Solaris Trusted Extensions as an integrated feature of the commercial OSs Solaris and OpenSolaris.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] In addition to the controlled access protection profile (CAPP), and role-based access control (RBAC) protection profiles, Trusted Extensions have also been certified at EAL4 to the labeled security protection profile (LSPP).
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] The security target includes both desktop and network functionality.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] LSPP mandates that users are not authorized to override the labeling policies enforced by the kernel and X Window System (X11 server).
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] The evaluation does not include a covert channel analysis.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Because these certifications depend on CAPP, no Common Criteria certifications suggest this product is trustworthy for MLS.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] BAE Systems offers XTS-400, a commercial system that supports MLS at what the vendor claims is "high assurance".
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Predecessor products (including the XTS-300) were evaluated at the TCSEC B3 level, which is MLS-capable.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] The XTS-400 has been evaluated under the Common Criteria at EAL5+ against the CAPP and LSPP protection profiles.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] CAPP and LSPP are both EAL3 protection profiles that are not inherently MLS-capable, but the security target for the Common Criteria evaluation of this product contains an enriched set of security functions that provide MLS capability.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Sanitization is a problem area for MLS systems.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Systems that implement MLS restrictions, like those defined by Bell–LaPadula model, only allow sharing when it obviously does not violate security restrictions.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Users with lower clearances can easily share their work with users holding higher clearances, but not vice versa.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] There is no efficient, reliable mechanism by which a Top Secret user can edit a Top Secret file, remove all Top Secret information, and then deliver it to users with Secret or lower clearances.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] In practice, MLS systems circumvent this problem via privileged functions that allow a trustworthy user to bypass the MLS mechanism and change a file's security classification.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Covert channels pose another problem for MLS systems.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] For an MLS system to keep secrets perfectly, there must be *no possible way* for a Top Secret process to transmit signals of any kind to a Secret or lower process.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] This includes side effects such as changes in available memory or disk space, or changes in process timing.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] When a process exploits such a side effect to transmit data, it is exploiting a covert channel.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] It is extremely difficult to close all covert channels in a practical computing system, and it may be impossible in practice.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] The process of identifying all covert channels is a challenging one by itself.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Most commercially available MLS systems do not attempt to close all covert channels, even though this makes it impractical to use them in high security applications.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Bypass is problematic when introduced as a means to treat a system high object as if it were MLS trusted.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] A common example is to extract data from a secret system high object to be sent to an unclassified destination, citing some property of the data as trusted evidence that it is 'really' unclassified (e.g.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] A system high system cannot be trusted to preserve any trusted evidence, and the result is that an overt data path is opened with no logical way to securely mediate it.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Bypass can be risky because, unlike narrow bandwidth covert channels that are difficult to exploit, bypass can present a large, easily exploitable overt leak in the system.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Bypass often arises out of failure to use trusted operating environments to maintain continuous separation of security domains all the way back to their origin.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] When that origin lies outside the system boundary, it may not be possible to validate the trusted separation to the origin.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] In that case, the risk of bypass can be unavoidable if the flow truly is essential.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] A common example of unavoidable bypass is a subject system that is required to accept secret IP packets from an untrusted source, encrypt the secret userdata and not the header and deposit the result to an untrusted network.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] The source lies outside the sphere of influence of the subject system.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Although the source is untrusted (e.g. system high) it is being trusted as if it were MLS because it provides packets that have unclassified headers and secret plaintext userdata, an MLS data construct.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Since the source is untrusted, it could be corrupt and place secrets in the unclassified packet header.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] The corrupted packet headers could be nonsense but it is impossible for the subject system to determine that with any reasonable reliability.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] The packet userdata is cryptographically well protected but the packet header can contain readable secrets.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] If the corrupted packets are passed to an untrusted network by the subject system they may not be routable but some cooperating corrupt process in the network could grab the packets and acknowledge them and the subject system may not detect the leak.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] This can be a large overt leak that is hard to detect.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Viewing classified packets with unclassified headers as system high structures instead of the MLS structures they really are presents a very common but serious threat.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Avoidable bypass often results when system architects design a system before correctly considering security, then attempt to apply security after the fact as add-on functions.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] In that situation, bypass appears to be the only (easy) way to make the system work.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Some pseudo-secure schemes are proposed (and approved!) that examine the contents of the bypassed data in a vain attempt to establish that bypassed data contains no secrets.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] This is not possible without trusting something about the data such as its format, which is contrary to the assumption that the source is not trusted to preserve any characteristics of the source data.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Assured "secure bypass" is a myth, just as a so-called High Assurance Guard (HAG) that transparently implements bypass.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] The risk these introduce has long been acknowledged; extant solutions are ultimately procedural, rather than technical.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] There is no way to know with certainty how much classified information is taken from our systems by exploitation of bypass.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Some laypersons are designing secure computing systems and drawing the conclusion that MLS does not exist.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] An explanation could be that there is a decline in COMPUSEC experts and the MLS term has been overloaded by two different meanings / uses.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] These two uses are: MLS as a processing environment vs MLS as a capability.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] The belief that MLS is non-existent is based on the belief that there are no products certified to operate in an MLS *environment* or mode and that therefore MLS as a *capability* does not exist.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Many systems operate in an environment containing data that has unequal security levels and therefore is MLS by the Computer Security Intermediate Value Theorem (CS-IVT).
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] The consequence of this confusion runs deeper.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] NSA-certified MLS operating systems, databases, and networks have existed in operational mode since the 1970s and that MLS products are continuing to be built, marketed, and deployed.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Laypersons often conclude that to admit that a system operates in an MLS environment (environment-centric meaning of MLS) is to be backed into the *perceived* corner of having a problem with no MLS solution (capability-centric meaning of MLS).
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] MLS is deceptively complex and just because simple solutions are not obvious does not justify a conclusion that they do not exist.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] This can lead to a crippling ignorance about COMPUSEC that manifests itself as whispers that "one cannot talk about MLS," and "There's no such thing as MLS." These MLS-denial schemes change so rapidly that they cannot be addressed.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Instead, it is important to clarify the distinction between MLS-environment and MLS-capable.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] The original use of the term MLS applied to the security environment, or mode.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] One solution to this confusion is to retain the original definition of MLS and be specific about MLS-capable when that context is used.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Security models such as the Biba model (for integrity) and the Bell–LaPadula model (for confidentiality) allow one-way flow between certain security domains that are otherwise assumed to be isolated.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] MILS addresses the isolation underlying MLS without addressing the controlled interaction between the domains addressed by the above models.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Trusted security-compliant channels mentioned above can link MILS domains to support more MLS functionality.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] The MILS approach pursues a strategy characterized by an older term, MSL (*multiple single level*), that isolates each level of information within its own single-level environment (System High).
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] The rigid process communication and isolation offered by MILS may be more useful to ultra high reliability software applications than MLS.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] MILS notably does not address the hierarchical structure that is embodied by the notion of security levels.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] This requires the addition of specific import/export applications between domains each of which needs to be accredited appropriately.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] As such, MILS might be better called Multiple Independent Domains of Security (MLS emulation on MILS would require a similar set of accredited applications for the MLS applications).
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Any MILS/MLS comparison should consider if the accreditation of a set of simpler export applications is more achievable than accreditation of one, more complex MLS kernel.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] This question depends in part on the extent of the import/export interactions that the stakeholders require.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] In favour of MILS is the possibility that not all the export applications will require maximal assurance.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] There is another way of solving such problems known as multiple single-level.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Each security level is isolated in a separate untrusted domain.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] The absence of a medium of communication between the domains assures no interaction is possible.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] The mechanism for this isolation is usually physical separation in separate computers.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] This is often used to support applications or operating systems which have no possibility of supporting MLS such as Microsoft Windows.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] The UCDMO ran a track specifically focused on MLS at the NSA Information Assurance Symposium in 2009, in which it highlighted several accredited (in production) and emergent MLS systems.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] There are several databases classified as MLS systems.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Oracle has a product named Oracle Label Security (OLS) that implements mandatory access controls - typically by adding a 'label' column to each table in an Oracle database.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] OLS is being deployed at the US Army INSCOM as the foundation of an "all-source" intelligence database spanning the JWICS and SIPRNet networks.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] There is a project to create a labeled version of PostgreSQL, and there are also older labeled-database implementations such as Trusted Rubix.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] These MLS database systems provide a unified back-end system for content spanning multiple labels, but they do not resolve the challenge of having users process content at multiple security levels in one system while enforcing mandatory access controls.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] There are also several MLS end-user applications.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] The other MLS capability currently on the UCDMO baseline is called MLChat Archived 2013-03-17 at the Wayback Machine, and it is a chat server that runs on the XTS-400 operating system - it was created by the US Naval Research Laboratory.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Given that content from users at different domains passes through the MLChat server, dirty-word scanning is employed to protect classified content, and there has been some debate about if this is truly an MLS system or more a form of cross-domain transfer data guard.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Mandatory access controls are maintained by a combination of XTS-400 and application-specific mechanisms.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] MLS applications not currently part of the UCDMO baseline include several applications from BlueSpace.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] BlueSpace has several MLS applications, including an MLS email client, an MLS search application and an MLS C2 system.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] BlueSpace uses a middleware strategy to enable its applications to be platform neutral, orchestrating one user interface across multiple Windows OS instances (virtualized or remote terminal sessions).
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] The US Naval Research Laboratory has also implemented a multilevel web application framework called MLWeb which integrates the Ruby on Rails framework with a multilevel database based on SQLite3.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Perhaps the greatest change going on in the multilevel security arena today is the convergence of MLS with virtualization.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] An increasing number of trusted operating systems are moving away from labeling files and processes, and are instead moving towards UNIX containers or virtual machines.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] Examples include zones in Solaris 10 TX, and the padded cell hypervisor in systems such as Green Hill's Integrity platform, and XenClient XT from Citrix.
[src:selinux-policy/multilevel-security] The High Assurance Platform from NSA as implemented in General Dynamics' Trusted Virtualization Environment (TVE) is another example - it uses SELinux at its core, and can support MLS applications that span multiple domains.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The **National Security Agency** (**NSA**) is an intelligence agency of the United States Department of Defense, under the authority of the director of national intelligence (DNI).
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The NSA is responsible for global monitoring, collection, and processing of information and data for intelligence and counterintelligence purposes, specializing in a discipline known as signals intelligence (SIGINT).
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The NSA is also tasked with the protection of U.S. communications networks and information systems.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The NSA relies on a variety of measures to accomplish its mission, the majority of which are clandestine.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Originating as a unit to decipher coded communications in World War II, it was officially formed as the NSA by President Harry S.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Between then and the end of the Cold War, it became the largest of the U.S. intelligence organizations in terms of personnel and budget.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Still, information available as of 2013 indicates that the Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) pulled ahead in this regard, with a budget of $14.7 billion.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The NSA currently conducts worldwide mass data collection and has been known to physically bug electronic systems as one method to this end.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The NSA is also alleged to have been behind such attack software as Stuxnet, which severely damaged Iran's nuclear program.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The NSA, alongside the CIA, maintains a physical presence in many countries across the globe; the CIA/NSA joint Special Collection Service (a highly classified intelligence team) inserts eavesdropping devices in high-value targets (such as presidential palaces or embassies).
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] SCS collection tactics allegedly encompass "close surveillance, burglary, wiretapping, [and] breaking".
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Unlike the CIA and the Defense Intelligence Agency (DIA), both of which specialize primarily in foreign human espionage, the NSA does not publicly conduct human intelligence gathering.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The NSA is entrusted with assisting with and coordinating SIGINT elements for other government organizations—which Executive Order prevents from engaging in such activities on their own.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] As part of these responsibilities, the agency has a co-located organization called the Central Security Service (CSS), which facilitates cooperation between the NSA and other U.S. defense cryptanalysis components.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] To further ensure streamlined communication between the signals intelligence community divisions, the NSA director simultaneously serves as the Commander of the United States Cyber Command and as Chief of the Central Security Service.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The NSA's actions have been a matter of political controversy on several occasions, including its role in providing intelligence during the Gulf of Tonkin incident, which contributed to the escalation of U.S. involvement in the Vietnam War.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Declassified documents later revealed that the NSA misinterpreted or overstated signals intelligence, leading to reports of a second North Vietnamese attack that likely never occurred.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The agency has also received scrutiny for spying on anti–Vietnam War leaders and the agency's participation in economic espionage.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] In 2013, the NSA had many of its secret surveillance programs revealed to the public by Edward Snowden, a former NSA contractor.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] According to the leaked documents, the NSA intercepts and stores the communications of over a billion people worldwide, including United States citizens.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The documents also revealed that the NSA tracks hundreds of millions of people's movements using cell phone metadata.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Internationally, research has pointed to the NSA's ability to surveil the domestic Internet traffic of foreign countries through "boomerang routing".
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The origins of the National Security Agency can be traced back to April 28, 1917, three weeks after the U.S.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Congress declared war on Germany in World War I.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] A code and cipher decryption unit was established as the Cable and Telegraph Section, which was also known as the Cipher Bureau.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] It was headquartered in Washington, D.C., and was part of the war effort under the executive branch without direct congressional authorization.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] During the war, it was relocated in the army's organizational chart several times.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] At that point, the unit consisted of Yardley and two civilian clerks.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] It absorbed the Navy's cryptanalysis functions in July 1918.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] World War I ended on November 11, 1918, and the army cryptographic section of Military Intelligence (MI-8) moved to New York City on May 20, 1919, where it continued intelligence activities as the Code Compilation Company under the direction of Yardley.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Army cryptographic section of military intelligence known as MI-8, the U.S. government created the Cipher Bureau, also known as Black Chamber, in 1919.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The Black Chamber was the United States' first peacetime cryptanalytic organization.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Jointly funded by the Army and the State Department, the Cipher Bureau was disguised as a New York City commercial code company; it produced and sold such codes for business use.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Its true mission, however, was to break the communications (chiefly diplomatic) of other nations.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] At the Washington Naval Conference, it aided American negotiators by providing them with the decrypted traffic of many of the conference delegations, including the Japanese.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The Black Chamber successfully persuaded Western Union, the largest U.S. telegram company at the time, as well as several other communications companies, to illegally give the Black Chamber access to cable traffic of foreign embassies and consulates.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Soon, these companies publicly discontinued their collaboration.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Despite the Chamber's initial successes, it was shut down in 1929 by U.S. secretary of state Henry L.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] During World War II, the Signal Intelligence Service (SIS) was created to intercept and decipher the communications of the Axis powers.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] When the war ended, the SIS was reorganized as the Army Security Agency (ASA), and it was placed under the leadership of the Director of Military Intelligence.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] On May 20, 1949, all cryptologic activities were centralized under a national organization called the Armed Forces Security Agency (AFSA).
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] This organization was originally established within the U.S.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Department of Defense under the command of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The AFSA was tasked with directing the Department of Defense communications and electronic intelligence activities, except those of U.S. military intelligence units.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] However, the AFSA was unable to centralize communications intelligence and failed to coordinate with civilian agencies that shared its interests, such as the Department of State, the Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) and the Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI).
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Truman ordered a panel to investigate how AFSA had failed to achieve its goals.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The results of the investigation led to improvements and its redesignation as the National Security Agency.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The National Security Council issued a memorandum of October 24, 1952, that revised National Security Council Intelligence Directive (NSCID) 9.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] On the same day, Truman issued a second memorandum that called for the establishment of the NSA.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The actual establishment of the NSA was done by a November 4 memo by Robert A.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Lovett, the Secretary of Defense, changing the name of the AFSA to the NSA, and making the new agency responsible for all communications intelligence.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Since President Truman's memo was a classified document, the existence of the NSA was not known to the public at that time.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Due to its ultra-secrecy, the U.S. intelligence community referred to the NSA as "No Such Agency".
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] In the 1960s, the NSA played a key role in expanding American commitment to the Vietnam War by providing evidence of a North Vietnamese attack on the American Naval destroyer USS *Maddox* during the Gulf of Tonkin incident.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] However, the project turned out to be controversial, and an internal review by the NSA concluded that its Minaret program was "disreputable if not outright illegal".
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The NSA has mounted a major effort to secure tactical communications among U.S. armed forces during the war with mixed success.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The NESTOR family of compatible secure voice systems it developed was widely deployed during the Vietnam War, with about 30,000 NESTOR sets produced.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] However, a variety of technical and operational problems limited their use, allowing the North Vietnamese to exploit and intercept U.S. communications.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The NSA tracked these individuals in a secret filing system that was destroyed in 1974.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Following the resignation of President Richard Nixon, there were several investigations into suspected misuse of FBI, CIA and NSA facilities.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Senator Frank Church uncovered previously unknown activity, such as a CIA plot (ordered by the administration of President John F.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The investigation also uncovered NSA's wiretaps on targeted U.S. citizens.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] After the Church Committee hearings, the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act of 1978 was passed.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] This was designed to limit the practice of mass surveillance in the United States.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] In 1986, the NSA intercepted the communications of the Libyan government during the immediate aftermath of the Berlin discotheque bombing.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The White House asserted that the NSA interception had provided "irrefutable" evidence that Libya was behind the bombing, which U.S.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] President Ronald Reagan cited as a justification for the 1986 United States bombing of Libya.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] In 1999, a multi-year investigation by the European Parliament highlighted the NSA's role in economic espionage in a report entitled 'Development of Surveillance Technology and Risk of Abuse of Economic Information'.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] That year, the NSA founded the NSA Hall of Honor, a memorial at the National Cryptologic Museum in Fort Meade, Maryland.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The memorial is a, "tribute to the pioneers and heroes who have made significant and long-lasting contributions to American cryptology".
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] NSA employees must be retired for more than fifteen years to qualify for the memorial.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] NSA's infrastructure deteriorated in the 1990s as defense budget cuts resulted in maintenance deferrals.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] On January 24, 2000, NSA headquarters suffered a total network outage for three days caused by an overloaded network.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Incoming traffic was successfully stored on agency servers, but it could not be directed and processed.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The agency carried out emergency repairs for $3 million to get the system running again (some incoming traffic was also directed instead to Britain's GCHQ for the time being).
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Director Michael Hayden called the outage a "wake-up call" for the need to invest in the agency's infrastructure.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] In the 1990s the defensive arm of the NSA—the Information Assurance Directorate (IAD)—started working more openly; the first public technical talk by an NSA scientist at a major cryptography conference was J.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Solinas' presentation on efficient Elliptic Curve Cryptography algorithms at Crypto 1997.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The IAD's cooperative approach to academia and industry culminated in its support for a transparent process for replacing the outdated Data Encryption Standard (DES) by an Advanced Encryption Standard (AES).
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] After the terrorist attacks of September 11, 2001, the NSA believed that it had public support for a dramatic expansion of its surveillance activities.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] In the aftermath of the September 11 attacks, the NSA created new IT systems to deal with the flood of information from new technologies like the Internet and cell phones.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] ThinThread contained advanced data mining capabilities.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] It also had a "privacy mechanism"; surveillance was stored encrypted; decryption required a warrant.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The research done under this program may have contributed to the technology used in later systems.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] ThinThread was canceled when Michael Hayden chose Trailblazer, which did not include ThinThread's privacy system.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Trailblazer Project ramped up in 2002 and was worked on by Science Applications International Corporation (SAIC), Boeing, Computer Sciences Corporation, IBM, and Litton Industries.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Some NSA whistleblowers complained internally about major problems surrounding Trailblazer.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] This led to investigations by Congress and the NSA and DoD Inspectors General.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] It was developed in small, inexpensive "test" pieces, rather than one grand plan like Trailblazer.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] It also included offensive cyber-warfare capabilities, like injecting malware into remote computers.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Congress criticized Turbulence in 2007 for having similar bureaucratic problems as Trailblazer.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] It was to be a realization of information processing at higher speeds in cyberspace.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The massive extent of the NSA's spying, both foreign and domestic, was revealed to the public in a series of detailed disclosures of internal NSA documents beginning in June 2013.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Most of the disclosures were leaked by former NSA contractor Edward Snowden.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] On 4 September 2020, the NSA's surveillance program was ruled unlawful by the US Court of Appeals.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The court also added that the US intelligence leaders, who publicly defended it, were not telling the truth.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] NSA's eavesdropping mission includes radio broadcasting, both from various organizations and individuals, the Internet, telephone calls, and other intercepted forms of communication.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Its secure communications mission includes military, diplomatic, and all other sensitive, confidential, or secret government communications.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] According to a 2010 article in *The Washington Post*, "every day, collection systems at the National Security Agency intercept and store 1.7 billion e-mails, phone calls and other types of communications.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Because of its listening task, NSA/CSS has been heavily involved in cryptanalytic research, continuing the work of predecessor agencies which had broken many World War II codes and ciphers (see, for instance, Purple, Venona project, and JN-25).
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] In 2004, NSA Central Security Service and the National Cyber Security Division of the Department of Homeland Security (DHS) agreed to expand the NSA Centers of Academic Excellence in Information Assurance Education Program.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] As part of the National Security Presidential Directive 54/Homeland Security Presidential Directive 23 (NSPD 54), signed on January 8, 2008, by President Bush, the NSA became the lead agency to monitor and protect all of the federal government's computer networks from cyber-terrorism.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] A part of the NSA's mission is to serve as a combat support agency for the Department of Defense.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] "Echelon" was created in the incubator of the Cold War.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Today it is a legacy system, and several NSA stations are closing.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Its capabilities were suspected to include the ability to monitor a large proportion of the world's transmitted civilian telephone, fax, and data traffic.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] During the early 1970s, the first of what became more than eight large satellite communications dishes were installed at Menwith Hill.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Investigative journalist Duncan Campbell reported in 1988 on the "ECHELON" surveillance program, an extension of the UKUSA Agreement on global signals intelligence SIGINT, and detailed how the eavesdropping operations worked.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] They confirmed that Menwith Hill was "linked directly to the headquarters of the US National Security Agency (NSA) at Fort Meade in Maryland".
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] NSA's United States Signals Intelligence Directive 18 (USSID 18) strictly prohibited the interception or collection of information about "...
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] U.S. persons, entities, corporations or organizations...." without explicit written legal permission from the United States Attorney General when the subject is located abroad, or the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Court when within U.S. borders.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Alleged Echelon-related activities, including its use for motives other than national security, including political and industrial espionage, received criticism from countries outside the UKUSA alliance.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The NSA was also involved in planning to blackmail people with "SEXINT", intelligence gained about a potential target's sexual activity and preferences.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Those targeted had not committed any apparent crime nor were they charged with one.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] To support its facial recognition program, the NSA is intercepting "millions of images per day".
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The Real Time Regional Gateway is a data collection program introduced in 2005 in Iraq by the NSA during the Iraq War that consisted of gathering all electronic communication, storing it, then searching and otherwise analyzing it.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] It was effective in providing information about Iraqi insurgents who had eluded less comprehensive techniques.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] This "collect it all" strategy introduced by NSA director, Keith B.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Alexander, is believed by Glenn Greenwald of *The Guardian* to be the model for the comprehensive worldwide mass archiving of communications which NSA is engaged in as of 2013.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] A dedicated unit of the NSA locates targets for the CIA for extrajudicial assassination in the Middle East.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The NSA has also spied extensively on the European Union, the United Nations, and numerous governments including allies and trading partners in Europe, South America, and Asia.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] In June 2015, WikiLeaks published documents showing that NSA spied on French companies.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] WikiLeaks also published documents showing that NSA spied on federal German ministries since the 1990s.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Even Germany's Chancellor Angela Merkel's cellphones and phones of her predecessors had been intercepted.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] In June 2013, Edward Snowden revealed that between 8 February and 8 March 2013, the NSA collected about 124.8 billion telephone data items and 97.1 billion computer data items throughout the world, as was displayed in charts from an internal NSA tool codenamed Boundless Informant.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Initially, it was reported that some of these data reflected eavesdropping on citizens in countries like Germany, Spain, and France, but later on, it became clear that those data were collected by European agencies during military missions abroad and were subsequently shared with NSA.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] This memo appears to give credence to previous speculation by cryptographers at Microsoft Research.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Edward Snowden claims that the NSA often bypasses the encryption process altogether by lifting information before encryption or after decryption.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Linus Torvalds, the founder of Linux kernel, joked during a LinuxCon keynote on September 18, 2013, that the NSA, who is the founder of SELinux, wanted a backdoor in the kernel.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] However, later, Linus' father, a Member of the European Parliament (MEP), revealed that the NSA actually did this.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] IBM Notes was the first widely adopted software product to use public key cryptography for client-server and server–server authentication and encryption of data.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Until US laws regulating encryption were changed in 2000, IBM and Lotus were prohibited from exporting versions of Notes that supported symmetric encryption keys that were longer than 40 bits.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] In 1997, Lotus negotiated an agreement with the NSA that allowed the export of a version that supported stronger keys with 64 bits, but 24 of the bits were encrypted with a special key and included in the message to provide a "workload reduction factor" for the NSA.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] This strengthened the protection for users of Notes outside the US against private-sector industrial espionage, but not against spying by the US government.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] While it is assumed that foreign transmissions terminating in the U.S.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] (such as a non-U.S. citizen accessing a U.S. website) subject non-U.S. citizens to NSA surveillance, recent research into boomerang routing has raised new concerns about the NSA's ability to surveil the domestic Internet traffic of foreign countries.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Boomerang routing occurs when an Internet transmission that originates and terminates in a single country transits another.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Research at the University of Toronto has suggested that approximately 25% of Canadian domestic traffic may be subject to NSA surveillance activities as a result of the boomerang routing of Canadian Internet service providers.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Intercepted packages are opened carefully by NSA employees.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] A document included in the NSA files released with Glenn Greenwald's book *No Place to Hide* details how the agency's Tailored Access Operations (TAO) and other NSA units gained access to hardware equipment.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] They intercepted routers, servers, and other network hardware equipment being shipped to organizations targeted for surveillance and installing covert implant firmware onto them before they are delivered.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Computers that were seized by the NSA due to interdiction are often modified with a physical device known as Cottonmouth.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] It is a device that can be inserted at the USB port of a computer to establish remote access to the targeted machine.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] NSA's mission, as outlined in Executive Order 12333 in 1981, is to collect information that constitutes "foreign intelligence or counterintelligence" while *not* "acquiring information concerning the domestic activities of United States persons".
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] NSA has declared that it relies on the FBI to collect information on foreign intelligence activities within the borders of the United States while confining its activities within the United States to the embassies and missions of foreign nations.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The appearance of a 'Domestic Surveillance Directorate' of the NSA was soon exposed as a hoax in 2013.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] NSA's domestic surveillance activities are limited by the requirements imposed by the Fourth Amendment to the U.S.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The specific requirements for domestic surveillance operations are contained in the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act of 1978 (FISA), which does not extend protection to non-U.S. citizens located outside of U.S. territory.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Bush, president during the 9/11 terrorist attacks, approved the Patriot Act shortly after the attacks to take anti-terrorist security measures.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Titles 1, 2, and 9 specifically authorized measures that would be taken by the NSA.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] These titles granted enhanced domestic security against terrorism, surveillance procedures, and improved intelligence, respectively.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] On March 10, 2004, there was a debate between President Bush and White House Counsel Alberto Gonzales, Attorney General John Ashcroft, and Acting Attorney General James Comey.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The Attorneys General were unsure if the NSA's programs could be considered constitutional.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] They threatened to resign over the matter, but ultimately the NSA's programs continued.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] On March 11, 2004, President Bush signed a new authorization for mass surveillance of Internet records, in addition to the surveillance of phone records.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] This allowed the president to be able to override laws such as the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act, which protected civilians from mass surveillance.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] In addition to this, President Bush also signed that the measures of mass surveillance were also retroactively in place.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] One such surveillance program, authorized by the U.S.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Signals Intelligence Directive 18 of President George Bush, was the Highlander Project undertaken for the National Security Agency by the U.S.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Army 513th Military Intelligence Brigade.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] NSA relayed telephone (including cell phone) conversations obtained from ground, airborne, and satellite monitoring stations to various U.S.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Army Signal Intelligence Officers, including the 201st Military Intelligence Battalion.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Conversations of citizens of the U.S. were intercepted, along with those of other nations.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Proponents of the surveillance program claim that the President has executive authority to order such action, arguing that laws such as FISA are overridden by the President's Constitutional powers.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] In addition, some argued that FISA was implicitly overridden by a subsequent statute, the Authorization for Use of Military Force, although the Supreme Court's ruling in *Hamdan v.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Under the PRISM program, which started in 2007, NSA gathers Internet communications from foreign targets from nine major U.S.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Internet-based communication service providers: Microsoft, Yahoo, Google, Facebook, PalTalk, AOL, Skype, YouTube and Apple.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Data gathered include email, videos, photos, VoIP chats such as Skype, and file transfers.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Former NSA director General Keith Alexander claimed that in September 2009 the NSA prevented Najibullah Zazi and his friends from carrying out a terrorist attack.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] However, no evidence has been presented demonstrating that the NSA has ever been instrumental in preventing a terrorist attack.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The FASCIA database stores various types of information, including Location Area Codes (LACs), Cell Tower IDs (CeLLIDs), Visitor Location Registers (VLRs), International Mobile Station Equipment Identity (IMEIs) and MSISDNs (Mobile Subscriber Integrated Services Digital Network-Numbers).
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Over about seven months, more than 27 terabytes of location data were collected and stored in the database.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Commercial Solutions for Classified (CSfC) is a key component of the NSA's commercial cybersecurity strategy.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] CSfC-validated commercial products are proven to meet rigorous security requirements for protection of classified National Security Systems (NSS) data.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Once validated, the Department of Defense (DoD), Intelligence Community, Military Services, and other U.S. government agencies are able to implement these commercial hardware and software technologies into their data protection and cybersecurity solutions.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Besides the more traditional ways of eavesdropping to collect signals intelligence, the NSA is also engaged in hacking computers, smartphones, and their networks.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] A division that conducts such operations is the Tailored Access Operations (TAO) division, which has been active since at least circa 1998.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The NSA is led by the Director of the National Security Agency (DIRNSA), who also serves as Chief of the Central Security Service (CHCSS) and Commander of the United States Cyber Command (USCYBERCOM) and is the highest-ranking military official of these organizations.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] He is assisted by a Deputy Director, who is the highest-ranking civilian within the NSA/CSS.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] NSA also has an Inspector General, head of the Office of the Inspector General (OIG); a General Counsel, head of the Office of the General Counsel (OGC); and a Director of Compliance, who is head of the Office of the Director of Compliance (ODOC).
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The National Security Agency Office of Inspector General has worked on cases in collaboration with the United States Department of Justice and the Central Intelligence Agency Office of Inspector General.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Unlike other intelligence organizations such as the CIA or DIA, the NSA has always been particularly reticent concerning its internal organizational structure.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Each of these directorates consisted of several groups or elements, designated by a letter.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] There were for example the A Group, which was responsible for all SIGINT operations against the Soviet Union and Eastern Europe, and the G Group, which was responsible for SIGINT related to all non-communist countries.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] These groups were divided into units designated by an additional number, like unit A5 for breaking Soviet codes, and G6, being the office for the Middle East, North Africa, Cuba, and Central and South America.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] As of 2013, NSA has about a dozen directorates, which are designated by a letter, although not all of them are publicly known.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] In the year 2000, a leadership team was formed consisting of the director, the deputy director, and the directors of the Signals Intelligence (SID), the Information Assurance (IAD) and the Technical Directorate (TD).
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The chiefs of other main NSA divisions became associate directors of the senior leadership team.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Bush initiated the President's Surveillance Program (PSP) in 2001, the NSA created a 24-hour Metadata Analysis Center (MAC), followed in 2004 by the Advanced Analysis Division (AAD), with the mission of analyzing content, Internet metadata and telephone metadata.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Both units were part of the Signals Intelligence Directorate.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] In 2016, a proposal combined the Signals Intelligence Directorate with the Information Assurance Directorate into a Directorate of Operations.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] NSANet stands for National Security Agency Network and is the official NSA intranet.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] It is a classified network, for information up to the level of TS/SCI to support the use and sharing of intelligence data between NSA and the signals intelligence agencies of the four other nations of the Five Eyes partnership.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The management of NSANet has been delegated to the Central Security Service Texas (CSSTEXAS).
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] NSANet is a highly secured computer network consisting of fiber-optic and satellite communication channels that are almost completely separated from the public Internet.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The network allows NSA personnel and civilian and military intelligence analysts anywhere in the world to have access to the agency's systems and databases.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] This access is tightly controlled and monitored.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] For example, every keystroke is logged, activities are audited at random, and downloading and printing of documents from NSANet are recorded.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] In 1998, NSANet, along with NIPRNet and SIPRNet, had "significant problems with poor search capabilities, unorganized data, and old information".
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] In 2004, the network was reported to have used over twenty commercial off-the-shelf operating systems.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Some universities that do highly sensitive research are allowed to connect to it.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The thousands of Top Secret internal NSA documents that were taken by Edward Snowden in 2013 were stored in "a file-sharing location on the NSA's intranet site"; so, they could easily be read online by NSA personnel.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Everyone with a TS/SCI clearance had access to these documents.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] As a system administrator, Snowden was responsible for moving accidentally misplaced highly sensitive documents to safer storage locations.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The NSA has its law enforcement team, known as the *NSA Police* (and formerly as *NSA Security Protective Force*) which provides law enforcement services, emergency response, and physical security to its officials and properties.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] NSA Police has a K9 division, which generally conducts explosive detection screening of mail, vehicles, and cargo entering NSA grounds.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] They use marked vehicles to carry out patrols.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The number of NSA employees is officially classified but there are several sources providing estimates.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] In 1961, the NSA had 59,000 military and civilian employees, which grew to 93,067 in 1969, of which 19,300 worked at the headquarters at Fort Meade.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] In the early 1980s, NSA had roughly 50,000 military and civilian personnel.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] By 1989 this number had grown again to 75,000, of which 25,000 worked at the NSA headquarters.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Between 1990 and 1995 the NSA's budget and workforce were cut by one-third, which led to a substantial loss of experience.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] In 2012, the NSA said more than 30,000 employees worked at Fort Meade and other facilities.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Inglis, the deputy director, said that the total number of NSA employees is "somewhere between 37,000 and one billion" as a joke, and stated that the agency is "probably the biggest employer of introverts." In 2013 *Der Spiegel* stated that the NSA had 40,000 employees.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] More widely, it has been described as the world's largest single employer of mathematicians.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Some NSA employees form part of the workforce of the National Reconnaissance Office (NRO), the agency that provides the NSA with satellite signals intelligence.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] As of 2013 about 1,000 system administrators work for the NSA.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The NSA received criticism early on in 1960 after two agents had defected to the Soviet Union.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Nonetheless, security breaches reoccurred only a year later when in an issue of *Izvestia* of July 23, 1963, a former NSA employee published several cryptologic secrets.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The very same day, an NSA clerk-messenger committed suicide as ongoing investigations disclosed that he had sold secret information to the Soviets regularly.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Edward Snowden's leaking of the existence of PRISM in 2013 caused the NSA to institute a "two-man rule", where two system administrators are required to be present when one accesses certain sensitive information.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Snowden claims he suggested such a rule in 2009.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The NSA conducts polygraph tests of employees.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] For new employees, the tests are meant to discover enemy spies who are applying to the NSA and to uncover any information that could make an applicant pliant to coercion.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] As part of the latter, historically *EPQs* or "embarrassing personal questions" about sexual behavior had been included in the NSA polygraph.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The NSA also conducts five-year periodic reinvestigation polygraphs of employees, focusing on counterintelligence programs.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] In addition, the NSA conducts periodic polygraph investigations to find spies and leakers; those who refuse to take them may receive "termination of employment", according to a 1982 memorandum from the director of the NSA.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] There are also "special access examination" polygraphs for employees who wish to work in highly sensitive areas, and those polygraphs cover counterintelligence questions and some questions about behavior.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] NSA's brochure states that the average test length is between two and four hours.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] Between 1974 and 1979, of the 20,511 job applicants who took polygraph tests, 695 (3.4%) confessed to previous felony crimes; almost all of those crimes had been undetected.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] In 2010 the NSA produced a video explaining its polygraph process.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The video, ten minutes long, is titled "The Truth About the Polygraph" and was posted to the Web site of the Defense Security Service.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] George Maschke, the founder of the Web site, accused the NSA polygraph video of being "Orwellian".
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] In 2013, an article indicated that after Edward Snowden revealed his identity in 2013, the NSA began requiring polygraphing of employees once per quarter.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] The number of exemptions from legal requirements has been criticized.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] When in 1964 Congress was hearing a bill giving the director of the NSA the power to fire at will any employee, *The Washington Post* wrote: "This is the very definition of arbitrariness.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p01] It means that an employee could be discharged and disgraced based on anonymous allegations without the slightest opportunity to defend himself." Yet, the bill was accepted by an overwhelming majority.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] When the agency was first established, its headquarters and cryptographic center were in the Naval Security Station in Washington, D.C.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The COMINT functions were located in Arlington Hall in Northern Virginia, which served as the headquarters of the U.S.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Because the Soviet Union had detonated a nuclear bomb and because the facilities were crowded, the federal government wanted to move several agencies, including the AFSA/NSA.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] A planning committee considered Fort Knox, but Fort Meade, Maryland, was ultimately chosen as NSA headquarters because it was far enough away from Washington, D.C. in case of a nuclear strike and was close enough so its employees would not have to move their families.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Construction of additional buildings began after the agency occupied buildings at Fort Meade in the late 1950s, which they soon outgrew.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] In 1963 the new headquarters building, nine stories tall, opened.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] NSA workers referred to the building as the "Headquarters Building" and since the NSA management occupied the top floor, workers used "Ninth Floor" to refer to their leaders.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] COMSEC remained in Washington, D.C., until its new building was completed in 1968.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] In September 1986, the Operations 2A and 2B buildings, both copper-shielded to prevent eavesdropping, opened with a dedication by President Ronald Reagan.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The four NSA buildings became known as the "Big Four." The NSA director moved to 2B when it opened.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Meade, Maryland, although it is separate from other compounds and agencies that are based within this same military installation.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Fort Meade is about 20 mi (32 km) southwest of Baltimore, and 25 mi (40 km) northeast of Washington, D.C.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The NSA has two dedicated exits off Baltimore–Washington Parkway.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The Eastbound exit from the Parkway (heading toward Baltimore) is open to the public and provides employee access to its main campus and public access to the National Cryptology Museum.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The Westbound side exit, (heading toward Washington) is labeled "NSA Employees Only".
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The exit may only be used by people with the proper clearances, and security vehicles parked along the road guard the entrance.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] NSA is the largest employer in the state of Maryland, and two-thirds of its personnel work at Fort Meade.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Built on 350 acres (140 ha; 0.55 sq mi) of Fort Meade's 5,000 acres (2,000 ha; 7.8 sq mi), the site has 1,300 buildings and an estimated 18,000 parking spaces.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] It contains 3,000,000 square feet (280,000 m2), or more than 68 acres (28 ha), of floor space; Bamford said that the U.S.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The facility has over 100 watchposts, one of them being the visitor control center, a two-story area that serves as the entrance.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] At the entrance, a white pentagonal structure, visitor badges are issued to visitors and security clearances of employees are checked.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The visitor center includes a painting of the NSA seal.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The OPS2A building, the tallest building in the NSA complex and the location of much of the agency's operations directorate is accessible from the visitor center.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Bamford described it as a "dark glass Rubik's Cube".
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The facility's "red corridor" houses non-security operations such as concessions and the drug store.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The name refers to the "red badge" which is worn by someone without a security clearance.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The NSA headquarters includes a cafeteria, a credit union, ticket counters for airlines and entertainment, a barbershop, and a bank.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] NSA headquarters has its own post office, fire department, and police force.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The employees at the NSA headquarters reside in various places in the Baltimore-Washington area, including Annapolis, Baltimore, and Columbia in Maryland and the District of Columbia, including the Georgetown community.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The NSA maintains a shuttle service from the Odenton station of MARC to its Visitor Control Center and has done so since 2005.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Following a major power outage in 2000, in 2003, and follow-ups through 2007, *The Baltimore Sun* reported that the NSA was at risk of electrical overload because of insufficient internal electrical infrastructure at Fort Meade to support the amount of equipment being installed.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] On August 6, 2006, *The Baltimore Sun* reported that the NSA had completely maxed out the grid and that Baltimore Gas & Electric (BGE, now Constellation Energy) was unable to sell them any more power.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] NSA decided to move some of its operations to a new satellite facility.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] BGE provided NSA with 65 to 75 megawatts at Fort Meade in 2007 and expected that an increase of 10 to 15 megawatts would be needed later that year.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] In 2011, the NSA was Maryland's largest consumer of power.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] In 2007, as BGE's largest customer, NSA bought as much electricity as Annapolis, the capital city of Maryland.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] One estimate put the potential for power consumption by the new Utah Data Center at US$40 million per year.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] In 1995, *The Baltimore Sun* reported that the NSA is the owner of the single largest group of supercomputers.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] NSA held a groundbreaking ceremony at Fort Meade in May 2013 for its High-Performance Computing Center 2, expected to open in 2016.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Called Site M, the center has a 150-megawatt power substation, 14 administrative buildings and 10 parking garages.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The center is 1,800,000 square feet (17 ha; 0.065 sq mi) and initially uses 60 megawatts of electricity.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Increments II and III are expected to be completed by 2030 and would quadruple the space, covering 5,800,000 square feet (54 ha; 0.21 sq mi) with 60 buildings and 40 parking garages.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Defense contractors are also establishing or expanding cybersecurity facilities near the NSA and around the Washington metropolitan area.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The DoD Computer Security Center was founded in 1981 and renamed the National Computer Security Center (NCSC) in 1985.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] NCSC was responsible for computer security throughout the federal government.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] NCSC was part of NSA, and during the late 1980s and the 1990s, NSA and NCSC published Trusted Computer System Evaluation Criteria in a six-foot high Rainbow Series of books that detailed trusted computing and network platform specifications.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The Rainbow books were replaced by the Common Criteria, however, in the early 2000s.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] In 2009, to protect its assets and access more electricity, NSA sought to decentralize and expand its existing facilities in Fort Meade and Menwith Hill, the latter expansion expected to be completed by 2015.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] On January 6, 2011, a groundbreaking ceremony was held to begin construction on the NSA's first Comprehensive National Cyber-security Initiative (CNCI) Data Center, known as the "Utah Data Center" for short.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The $1.5B data center is being built at Camp Williams, Utah, located 25 miles (40 km) south of Salt Lake City, and will help support the agency's National Cyber-security Initiative.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] It is expected to be operational by September 2013.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Construction of Utah Data Center finished in May 2019.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] In 2012, NSA collected intelligence from four geostationary satellites.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Satellite receivers were at Roaring Creek Station in Catawissa, Pennsylvania and Salt Creek Station in Arbuckle, California.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] It operated ten to twenty taps on U.S. telecom switches.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] NSA had installations in several U.S. states and from them observed intercepts from Europe, the Middle East, North Africa, Latin America, and Asia.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The *Yakima Herald-Republic* cited Bamford, saying that many of NSA's bases for its Echelon program were a legacy system, using outdated, 1990s technology.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] In 2004, NSA closed its operations at Bad Aibling Station (Field Station 81) in Bad Aibling, Germany.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] In 2012, NSA began to move some of its operations at Yakima Research Station, Yakima Training Center, in Washington state to Colorado, planning to leave Yakima closed.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] During 2013, NSA also intended to close operations at Sugar Grove, West Virginia.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] NSA operates RAF Menwith Hill in North Yorkshire, United Kingdom, which was, according to BBC News in 2007, the largest electronic monitoring station in the world.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The agency's European Cryptologic Center (ECC), with 240 employees in 2011, is headquartered at a US military compound in Griesheim, near Frankfurt in Germany.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] A 2011 NSA report indicates that the ECC is responsible for the "largest analysis and productivity in Europe" and focuses on various priorities, including Africa, Europe, the Middle East, and counterterrorism operations.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Since the mid-1980s, the NSA and Taiwan's National Security Bureau have jointly operated a signals intelligence (SIGINT) listening station at Yangmingshan.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] In 2013, a new Consolidated Intelligence Center, also to be used by NSA, is being built at the headquarters of the United States Army Europe in Wiesbaden, Germany.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] NSA's partnership with Bundesnachrichtendienst (BND), the German foreign intelligence service, was confirmed by BND president Gerhard Schindler.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Thailand is a "3rd party partner" of the NSA along with nine other nations.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] These are non-English-speaking countries that have made security agreements for the exchange of SIGINT raw material and end product reports.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Thailand is the site of at least two US SIGINT collection stations.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] One is at the US Embassy in Bangkok, an NSA-CIA Joint Special Collection Service (JSCS) unit.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] It presumably eavesdrops on foreign consulates, embassies, governmental communications, and other targets of opportunity.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The second installation is a FORNSAT (foreign satellite interception) station in the Thai city of Khon Kaen.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] It is codenamed INDRA, but has also been referred to as LEMONWOOD.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The station is approximately 40 hectares (99 acres) in size and consists of a large 3,700–4,600 m2 (40,000–50,000 ft2) operations building on the west side of the ops compound and four radome-enclosed parabolic antennas.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Possibly two of the radome-enclosed antennas are used for SATCOM intercept and two antennas are used for relaying the intercepted material back to the NSA.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] There is also a PUSHER-type circularly-disposed antenna array (CDAA) just north of the ops compound.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] NSA activated Khon Kaen in October 1979.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Its mission was to eavesdrop on the radio traffic of Chinese army and air force units in southern China, especially in and around the city of Kunming in Yunnan Province.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The base fell into disrepair in the 1990s as China and Vietnam became more friendly towards the US, and by 2002 archived satellite imagery showed that the PUSHER CDAA antenna had been torn down, perhaps indicating that the base had been closed.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] At some point in the period since 9/11, the Khon Kaen base was reactivated and expanded to include a sizeable SATCOM intercept mission.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] It is likely that the NSA presence at Khon Kaen is relatively small, and that most of the work is done by civilian contractors.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] NSA has been involved in debates about public policy, both indirectly as a behind-the-scenes adviser to other departments, and directly during and after Vice Admiral Bobby Ray Inman's directorship.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] NSA was a major player in the debates of the 1990s regarding the export of cryptography in the United States.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Restrictions on export were reduced but not eliminated in 1996.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Its secure government communications work has involved the NSA in numerous technology areas, including the design of specialized communications hardware and software, production of dedicated semiconductors at the Ft.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Meade chip fabrication plant), and advanced cryptography research.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] For 50 years, the NSA designed and built most of its in-house computer equipment, but from the 1990s until about 2003 (when the U.S.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Congress curtailed the practice), the agency contracted with the private sector in the fields of research and equipment.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] NSA was embroiled in some controversy concerning its involvement in the creation of the Data Encryption Standard (DES), a standard and public block cipher algorithm used by the U.S. government and banking community.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] During the development of DES by IBM in the 1970s, NSA recommended changes to some details of the design.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] It has since been observed that the S-boxes in DES are particularly resilient against differential cryptanalysis, a technique that was not publicly discovered until the late 1980s but known to the IBM DES team.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The involvement of the NSA in selecting a successor to the Data Encryption Standard (DES), the Advanced Encryption Standard (AES), was limited to hardware performance testing.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] NSA has subsequently certified AES for protection of classified information when used in NSA-approved systems.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The widely used SHA-1 and SHA-2 hash functions were designed by NSA.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] SHA-1 is a slight modification of the weaker SHA-0 algorithm, also designed by NSA in 1993.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] This small modification was suggested by the NSA two years later, with no justification other than the fact that it provides additional security.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] An attack for SHA-0 that does not apply to the revised algorithm was indeed found between 1998 and 2005 by academic cryptographers.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Because of weaknesses and key length restrictions in SHA-1, NIST deprecates its use for digital signatures and approves only the newer SHA-2 algorithms for such applications from 2013 on.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] A new hash standard, SHA-3, has recently been selected through the competition concluded on October 2, 2012, with the selection of Keccak as the algorithm.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The process to select SHA-3 was similar to the one held in choosing the AES, but some doubts have been cast over it, since fundamental modifications have been made to Keccak to turn it into a standard.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] These changes potentially undermine the cryptanalysis performed during the competition and reduce the security levels of the algorithm.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The proposal was strongly opposed and key escrow requirements ultimately went nowhere.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] However, NSA's Fortezza hardware-based encryption cards, created for the Clipper project, are still used within government, and NSA ultimately declassified and published the design of the Skipjack cipher used on the cards.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] NSA promoted the inclusion of a random number generator called Dual EC DRBG in the U.S.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] National Institute of Standards and Technology's 2007 guidelines.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] This led to speculation of a backdoor which would allow NSA access to data encrypted by systems using that pseudorandom number generator (PRNG).
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] This is now deemed to be plausible based on the fact that output of next iterations of PRNG can provably be determined if relation between two internal Elliptic Curve points is known.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Both NIST and RSA are now officially recommending against the use of this PRNG.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Perfect Citizen is a program to perform vulnerability assessment by the NSA in the American critical infrastructure.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] It was originally reported to be a program to develop a system of sensors to detect cyber attacks on critical infrastructure computer networks in both the private and public sector through a network monitoring system named *Einstein*.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] It is funded by the Comprehensive National Cybersecurity Initiative and thus far Raytheon has received a contract for up to $100 million for the initial stage.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The NSA has invested many millions of dollars in academic research under grant code prefix *MDA904*, resulting in over 3,000 papers as of October 11, 2007.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The NSA publishes its documents through various publications.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Despite this, the NSA/CSS has, at times, attempted to restrict the publication of academic research into cryptography; for example, the Khufu and Khafre block ciphers were voluntarily withheld in response to an NSA request to do so.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] In response to a FOIA lawsuit, in 2013 the NSA released the 643-page research paper titled, "Untangling the Web: A Guide to Internet Research", written and compiled by NSA employees to assist other NSA workers in searching for information of interest to the agency on the public Internet.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Patent and Trademark Office under gag order.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Unlike normal patents, these are not revealed to the public and do not expire.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] However, if the Patent Office receives an application for an identical patent from a third party, they will reveal the NSA's patent and officially grant it to the NSA for the full term on that date.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] One of NSA's published patents describes a method of geographically locating an individual computer site in an Internet-like network, based on the latency of multiple network connections.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Although no public patent exists, NSA is reported to have used a similar locating technology called trilateralization that allows real-time tracking of an individual's location, including altitude from ground level, using data obtained from cellphone towers.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The heraldic insignia of NSA consists of an eagle inside a circle, grasping a key in its talons.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The eagle represents the agency's national mission.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Its breast features a shield with bands of red and white, taken from the Great Seal of the United States and representing Congress.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The key is taken from the emblem of Saint Peter and represents security.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] When the NSA was created, the agency had no emblem and used that of the Department of Defense.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The agency adopted its first of two emblems in 1963.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The current NSA insignia has been in use since 1965, when then-Director, LTG Marshall S.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Carter (USA) ordered the creation of a device to represent the agency.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The NSA's flag consists of the agency's seal on a light blue background.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Crews associated with NSA missions have been involved in several dangerous and deadly situations.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The USS *Liberty* incident in 1967 and USS *Pueblo* incident in 1968 are examples of the losses endured during the Cold War.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The National Security Agency/Central Security Service Cryptologic Memorial honors and remembers the fallen personnel, both military and civilian, of these intelligence missions.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] It is made of black granite, and has 171 names carved into it, as of 2013.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] A tradition of declassifying the stories of the fallen was begun in 2001.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] In the United States, at least since 2001, there has been legal controversy over what signal intelligence can be used for and how much freedom the National Security Agency has to use signal intelligence.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] In 2015, the government made slight changes in how it uses and collects certain types of data, specifically phone records.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The government was not analyzing the phone records as of early 2019.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The surveillance programs were deemed unlawful in September 2020 in a court of appeals case.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] On December 16, 2005, *The New York Times* reported that under White House pressure and with an executive order from President George W.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Edward Snowden is a former American intelligence contractor who revealed in 2013 the existence of secret wide-ranging information-gathering programs conducted by the National Security Agency (NSA).
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] More specifically, Snowden released information that demonstrated how the United States government was gathering immense amounts of personal communications, emails, phone locations, web histories and more of American citizens without their knowledge.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] One of Snowden's primary motivators for releasing this information was fear of a surveillance state developing as a result of the infrastructure being created by the NSA.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] As Snowden recounts, "I believe that, at this point in history, the greatest danger to our freedom and way of life comes from the reasonable fear of omniscient State powers kept in check by nothing more than policy documents...
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] It is not that I do not value intelligence, but that I oppose . . . omniscient, automatic, mass surveillance. . . .
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] On January 17, 2006, the Center for Constitutional Rights filed a lawsuit, CCR v.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The lawsuit challenged the National Security Agency's (NSA's) surveillance of people within the U.S., including the interception of CCR emails without securing a warrant first.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] District Court Judge Anna Diggs Taylor concluded that NSA's warrantless surveillance program was both illegal and unconstitutional.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] On July 6, 2007, the 6th Circuit Court of Appeals vacated the decision because the ACLU lacked standing to bring the suit.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] As a result of the USA Freedom Act passed by Congress in June 2015, the NSA had to shut down its bulk phone surveillance program on November 29 of the same year.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The USA Freedom Act forbids the NSA to collect metadata and content of phone calls unless it has a warrant for terrorism investigation.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] In that case, the agency must ask the telecom companies for the record, which will only be kept for six months.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The NSA's use of large telecom companies to assist it with its surveillance efforts has caused several privacy concerns.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] In May 2008, Mark Klein, a former AT&T employee, alleged that his company had cooperated with NSA in installing Narus hardware to replace the FBI Carnivore program, to monitor network communications including traffic between U.S. citizens.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] NSA was reported in 2008 to use its computing capability to analyze "transactional" data that it regularly acquires from other government agencies, which gather it under their jurisdictional authorities.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] A 2013 advisory group for the Obama administration, seeking to reform NSA spying programs following the revelations of documents released by Edward J.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Clarke was a group member and stated on April 11, 2014, that NSA had no advance knowledge of Heartbleed.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Law enforcement agents were directed to conceal how the investigations began and recreate a legal investigative trail by re-obtaining the same evidence by other means.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] In the months leading to April 2009, the NSA intercepted the communications of U.S. citizens, including a congressman, although the Justice Department believed that the interception was unintentional.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The Justice Department then took action to correct the issues and bring the program into compliance with existing laws.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] United States Attorney General Eric Holder resumed the program according to his understanding of the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act amendment of 2008, without explaining what had occurred.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Polls conducted in June 2013 found divided results among Americans regarding NSA's secret data collection.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Rasmussen Reports found that 59% of Americans disapprove, Gallup found that 53% disapprove, and Pew found that 56% are in favor of NSA data collection.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] On April 25, 2013, the NSA obtained a court order requiring Verizon's Business Network Services to provide metadata on all calls in its system to the NSA "on an ongoing daily basis" for three months, as reported by *The Guardian* on June 6, 2013.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] This information includes "the numbers of both parties on a call ... location data, call duration, unique identifiers, and the time and duration of all calls" but not "[t]he contents of the conversation itself".
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The order relies on the so-called "business records" provision of the Patriot Act.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] In August 2013, following the Snowden leaks, new details about the NSA's data mining activity were revealed.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Reportedly, the majority of emails into or out of the United States are captured at "selected communications links" and automatically analyzed for keywords or other "selectors".
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The utility of such a massive metadata collection in preventing terrorist attacks is disputed.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Many studies reveal the dragnet-like system to be ineffective.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Defenders of the program said that while metadata alone cannot provide all the information necessary to prevent an attack, it assures the ability to "connect the dots" between suspect foreign numbers and domestic numbers with a speed only the NSA's software is capable of.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] One benefit of this is quickly being able to determine the difference between suspicious activity and real threats.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] As an example, NSA director General Keith B.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Alexander mentioned at the annual Cybersecurity Summit in 2013, that metadata analysis of domestic phone call records after the Boston Marathon bombing helped determine that rumors of a follow-up attack in New York were baseless.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] In addition to doubts about its effectiveness, many people argue that the collection of metadata is an unconstitutional invasion of privacy.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] As of 2015, the collection process remained legal and grounded in the ruling from *Smith v.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] A prominent opponent of the data collection and its legality is U.S.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] As of May 7, 2015, the United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit ruled that the interpretation of Section 215 of the Patriot Act was wrong and that the NSA program that has been collecting Americans' phone records in bulk is illegal.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] It stated that Section 215 cannot be interpreted to allow government to collect national phone data and, as a result, expired on June 1, 2015.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Under the Upstream collection program, the NSA paid telecommunications companies hundreds of millions of dollars in order to collect data from them.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] While companies such as Google and Yahoo! claim that they do not provide "direct access" from their servers to the NSA unless under a court order, the NSA had access to emails, phone calls, and cellular data users.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Under this new ruling, telecommunications companies maintain bulk user metadata on their servers for at least 18 months, to be provided upon request to the NSA.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] This ruling made the mass storage of specific phone records at NSA datacenters illegal, but it did not rule on Section 215's constitutionality.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] In a declassified document it was revealed that 17,835 phone lines were on an improperly permitted "alert list" from 2006 to 2009 in breach of compliance, which tagged these phone lines for daily monitoring.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Eleven percent of these monitored phone lines met the agency's legal standard for "reasonably articulable suspicion" (RAS).
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The NSA tracks the locations of hundreds of millions of cell phones per day, allowing it to map people's movements and relationships in detail.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The NSA has been reported to have access to all communications made via Google, Microsoft, Facebook, Yahoo, YouTube, AOL, Skype, Apple and Paltalk, and collects hundreds of millions of contact lists from personal email and instant messaging accounts each year.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] It has also managed to weaken much of the encryption used on the Internet (by collaborating with, coercing, or otherwise infiltrating numerous technology companies to leave "backdoors" into their systems) so that the majority of encryption is inadvertently vulnerable to different forms of attack.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Domestically, the NSA has been proven to collect and store metadata records of phone calls, including over 120 million US Verizon subscribers, as well as intercept vast amounts of communications via the internet (Upstream).
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The government's legal standing had been to rely on a secret interpretation of the Patriot Act whereby the entirety of US communications may be considered "relevant" to a terrorism investigation if it is expected that even a tiny minority may relate to terrorism.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The NSA also supplies foreign intercepts to the DEA, IRS and other law enforcement agencies, who use these to initiate criminal investigations.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Federal agents are then instructed to "recreate" the investigative trail via parallel construction.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The NSA also spies on influential Muslim societies to obtain information that could be used to discredit them, such as their use of pornography.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The targets, both domestic and abroad, are not suspected of any crime but hold religious or political views deemed "radical" by the NSA.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] According to a report in *The Washington Post* in July 2014, relying on information provided by Snowden, 90% of those placed under surveillance in the U.S. are ordinary Americans and are not the intended targets.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The newspaper said it had examined documents including emails, text messages, and online accounts that support the claim.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The Intelligence Committees of the US House and Senate exercise primary oversight over the NSA; other members of Congress have been denied access to materials and information regarding the agency and its activities.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The United States Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Court, the secret court charged with regulating the NSA's activities is, according to its chief judge, incapable of investigating or verifying how often the NSA breaks even its own secret rules.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] It has since been reported that the NSA violated its own rules on data access thousands of times a year, many of these violations involving large-scale data interceptions.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The NSA has "generally disregarded the special rules for disseminating United States person information" by illegally sharing its intercepts with different law enforcement agencies.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Email contact lists (including those of US citizens) are collected at numerous foreign locations to work around the illegality of doing so on US soil.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Legal opinions on the NSA's bulk collection program have differed.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Surely, such a program infringes on 'that degree of privacy' that the Founders enshrined in the Fourth Amendment.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] District Judge William Pauley ruled that the NSA's collection of telephone records is legal and valuable in the fight against terrorism.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] In his opinion, he wrote, "a bulk telephony metadata collection program [is] a wide net that could find and isolate gossamer contacts among suspected terrorists in an ocean of seemingly disconnected data" and noted that a similar collection of data before 9/11 might have prevented the attack.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] At a March 2013 Senate Intelligence Committee hearing, Senator Ron Wyden asked the Director of National Intelligence James Clapper, "Does the NSA collect any type of data at all on millions or hundreds of millions of Americans?" Clapper replied "No, sir. ...
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] On July 31 NSA Deputy Director John Inglis conceded to the Senate that these intercepts had not been vital in stopping any terrorist attacks, but were "close" to vital in identifying and convicting four San Diego men for sending US$8,930 to Al-Shabaab, a militia that conducts terrorism in Somalia.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The U.S. government has aggressively sought to dismiss and challenge Fourth Amendment cases raised against it, and has granted retroactive immunity to ISPs and telecoms participating in domestic surveillance.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The U.S. military has acknowledged blocking access to parts of *The Guardian* website for thousands of defense personnel across the country, and blocking the entire *Guardian* website for personnel stationed throughout Afghanistan, the Middle East, and South Asia.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] In October 2014, the United Nations report condemned mass surveillance programs carried out by the U.S. intelligence communities and other nations as violating multiple global treaties and conventions that guaranteed core privacy rights.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] An exploit dubbed EternalBlue, created by the NSA, was used in the WannaCry ransomware attack in May 2017.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The exploit had been leaked online by a hacking group, The Shadow Brokers, nearly a month before the attack.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Several experts have pointed the finger at the NSA's non-disclosure of the underlying vulnerability, and their loss of control over the EternalBlue attack tool that exploited it.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Edward Snowden said that if the NSA had "privately disclosed the flaw used to attack hospitals when they found it, not when they lost it, [the attack] might not have happened".
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Former employee David Evenden, who had left the NSA to work for US defense contractor Cyperpoint at a position in the United Arab Emirates, was tasked with hacking UAE neighbor Qatar in 2015 to determine if they were funding terrorist group Muslim Brotherhood.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] He quit the company after learning his team had hacked Qatari Sheikha Moza bint Nasser's email exchanges with Michelle Obama, just before she visited Doha.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] Upon Evenden's return to the US, he reported his experiences to the FBI.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] The incident highlights a growing trend of former NSA employees and contractors leaving the agency to start up their firms, and then hiring out to countries like Turkey, Sudan, and even Russia, a country involved in numerous cyberattacks against the US.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] In May 2021, it was reported that the Danish Defence Intelligence Service collaborated with the NSA to wiretap on fellow EU members and leaders, leading to wide backlash among EU countries and demands for explanation from Danish and American governments.
[src:selinux-policy/national-security-agency-p02] NSA director Paul Nakasone disclosed in a letter to Representative Ron Wyden that the NSA buys data without a warrant.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] SELinux is a set of kernel modifications and user-space tools that have been added to various Linux distributions.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] Its architecture strives to separate enforcement of security decisions from the security policy, and streamlines the amount of software involved with security policy enforcement.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] The key concepts underlying SELinux can be traced to several earlier projects by the United States National Security Agency (NSA).
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] A Linux kernel integrating SELinux enforces mandatory access control policies that confine user programs and system services, as well as access to files and network resources.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] Limiting privilege to the minimum required to work reduces or eliminates the ability of these programs and daemons to cause harm if faulty or compromised (for example via buffer overflows or misconfigurations).
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] This confinement mechanism operates independently of the traditional Linux (discretionary) access control mechanisms.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] It has no concept of a "root" superuser, and does not share the well-known shortcomings of the traditional Linux security mechanisms, such as a dependence on setuid/setgid binaries.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] The security of an "unmodified" Linux system (a system without SELinux) depends on the correctness of the kernel, of all the privileged applications, and of each of their configurations.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] A fault in any one of these areas may allow the compromise of the entire system.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] In contrast, the security of a "modified" system (based on an SELinux kernel) depends primarily on the correctness of the kernel and its security-policy configuration.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] While problems with the correctness or configuration of applications may allow the limited compromise of individual user programs and system daemons, they do not necessarily pose a threat to the security of other user programs and system daemons or to the security of the system as a whole.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] From a purist perspective, SELinux provides a hybrid of concepts and capabilities drawn from mandatory access controls, mandatory integrity controls, role-based access control (RBAC), and type enforcement architecture.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] Third-party tools enable one to build a variety of security policies.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] SELinux was designed to demonstrate the value of mandatory access controls to the Linux community and how such controls could be added to Linux.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] Originally, the patches that make up SELinux had to be explicitly applied to the Linux kernel source; SELinux was merged into the Linux kernel mainline in the 2.6 series of the Linux kernel.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] The NSA, the original primary developer of SELinux, released the first version to the open source development community under the GNU GPL on 22 December 2000.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] The software was merged into the mainline Linux kernel 2.6.0-test3, released on 8 August 2003.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] Other significant contributors include Red Hat, Network Associates, Secure Computing Corporation, Tresys Technology, and Trusted Computer Solutions.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] Experimental ports of the FLASK/TE implementation have been made available via the TrustedBSD Project for the FreeBSD and Darwin operating systems.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] Security-Enhanced Linux implements the Flux Advanced Security Kernel (FLASK).
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] Such a kernel contains architectural components prototyped in the Fluke operating system.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] These provide general support for enforcing many kinds of mandatory access control policies, including those based on the concepts of type enforcement, role-based access control, and multilevel security.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] FLASK, in turn, was based on DTOS, a Mach-derived Distributed Trusted Operating System developed as a part of earlier research in mandatory access control systems.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] A comprehensive list of the original and external contributors to SELinux was hosted at the NSA website until maintenance ceased sometime in 2009.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] The following list reproduces the original as preserved by the Internet Archive Wayback Machine.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] The scope of their contributions was listed in the page and has been omitted for brevity, but it can be accessed through the archived copy.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] SELinux users and roles do not have to be related to the actual system users and roles.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] For every current user or process, SELinux assigns a three string context consisting of a username, role, and domain (or type).
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] This system is more flexible than normally required: as a rule, most of the real users share the same SELinux username, and all access control is managed through the third tag, the domain.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] The circumstances under which a process is allowed into a certain domain must be configured in the policies.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] The command `runcon` allows for the launching of a process into an explicitly specified context (user, role, and domain), but SELinux may deny the transition if it is not approved by the policy.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] Files, network ports, and other hardware also have an SELinux context, consisting of a name, role (seldom used), and type.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] In the case of file systems, mapping between files and the security contexts is called labeling.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] The labeling is defined in policy files but can also be manually adjusted without changing the policies.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] Hardware types are quite detailed, for instance, `bin_t` (all files in the folder /bin) or `postgresql_port_t` (PostgreSQL port, 5432).
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] The SELinux context for a remote file system can be specified explicitly at mount time.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] SELinux adds the `-Z` switch to the shell commands `ls`, `ps`, and some others, allowing the security context of the files or process to be seen.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] Typical policy rules consist of explicit permissions, for example, which domains the user must possess to perform certain actions with the given target (read, execute, or, in case of network port, bind or connect), and so on.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] More complex mappings are also possible, involving roles and security levels.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] A typical policy consists of a mapping (labeling) file, a rule file, and an interface file, that define the domain transition.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] These three files must be compiled together with the SELinux tools to produce a single policy file.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] The resulting policy file can be loaded into the kernel to make it active.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] Loading and unloading policies does not require a reboot.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] The policy files are either hand written or can be generated from the more user friendly SELinux management tool.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] They are normally tested in permissive mode first, where violations are logged but allowed.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] The `audit2allow` tool can be used later to produce additional rules that extend the policy to allow all legitimate activities of the application being confined.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] SELinux has been implemented in Android since version 4.3.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] Among free community-supported Linux distributions, Fedora was one of the earliest adopters, including support for it by default since Fedora Core 2.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] Other distributions include support for it such as Debian as of version 9 Stretch release and Ubuntu as of 8.04 Hardy Heron.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] As of version 11.1, openSUSE contains SELinux "basic enablement".
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] SUSE Linux Enterprise (SLE) 11 features SELinux as a "technology preview".
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] SELinux is popular in systems based on Linux containers, such as CoreOS Container Linux and rkt.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] It is useful as an additional security control to help further enforce isolation between deployed containers and their host.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] SELinux is available since 2005 as part of Red Hat Enterprise Linux (RHEL) version 4 and all future releases.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] This presence is also reflected in corresponding versions of derived systems such as CentOS, Scientific Linux, AlmaLinux and Rocky Linux.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] The supported policy in RHEL4 is targeted policy which aims for maximum ease of use and thus is not as restrictive as it might be.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] Future versions of RHEL are planned to have more targets in the targeted policy which will mean more restrictive policies.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] RHEL version 5 introduced multilevel security (MLS) policy for servers only.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] Fedora Linux 10 introduced a minimum policy, designed for certain platforms such as low-memory devices and virtual machines.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] openSUSE Tumbleweed transitioned from AppArmor to SELinux for new installation since 11 February 2025, and SLE/openSUSE Leap 16 was shipped with SELinux by default as well. openSUSE/SLE adopted RHEL/Fedora policies for its SELinux implementation although with some differences.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] AppArmor is retained for existing Tumbleweed and SLE/openSUSE Leap 15.x installation (users can manually migrate their existing installation to SELinux).
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] AppArmor is also available as an install-time selection for Tumbleweed users, but not on SLE/Leap 16.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] SELinux can potentially control which activities a system allows each user, process, and daemon, with very precise specifications.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] It is used to confine daemons such as database engines or web servers that have clearly defined data access and activity rights.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] This limits potential harm from a confined daemon that becomes compromised.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] SELinux represents one of several possible approaches to the problem of restricting the actions that installed software can take.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] Another popular alternative is called AppArmor and is available on SUSE Linux Enterprise Server (SLES), openSUSE, and Debian-based platforms.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] AppArmor was developed as a component to the now-defunct Immunix Linux platform.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] Because AppArmor and SELinux differ radically from one another, they form distinct alternatives for software control.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] Whereas SELinux re-invents certain concepts to provide access to a more expressive set of policy choices, AppArmor was designed to be simple by extending the same administrative semantics used for DAC up to the mandatory access control level.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] Isolation of processes can also be accomplished by mechanisms such as virtualization.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] The NSA has adopted some of the SELinux concepts in Security-Enhanced Android.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] General Dynamics builds and distributes PitBull Trusted Operating System, a multilevel security (MLS) enhancement for Red Hat Enterprise Linux.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] Multi-Category Security (MCS) is an enhancement to SELinux for Red Hat Enterprise Linux that allows users to label files with categories, in order to further restrict access through discretionary access control and type enforcement.
[src:selinux-policy/security-enhanced-linux] Categories provide additional compartments within sensitivity levels used by multilevel security (MLS).
[src:selinux-policy/type-enforcement] The concept of **type enforcement** (**TE**), in the field of information technology, is an access control mechanism for regulating access in computer systems.
[src:selinux-policy/type-enforcement] Implementing TE gives priority to mandatory access control (MAC) over discretionary access control (DAC).
[src:selinux-policy/type-enforcement] Access clearance is first given to a subject (e.g. process) accessing objects (e.g. files, records, messages) based on rules defined in an attached security context.
[src:selinux-policy/type-enforcement] A security context in a domain is defined by a domain security policy.
[src:selinux-policy/type-enforcement] In the Linux security module (LSM) in SELinux, the security context is an extended attribute.
[src:selinux-policy/type-enforcement] Type enforcement implementation is a prerequisite for MAC, and a first step before multilevel security (MLS) or its replacement multi categories security (MCS).
[src:selinux-policy/type-enforcement] It is a complement of role-based access control (RBAC).
[src:selinux-policy/type-enforcement] Type enforcement implies fine-grained control over the operating system, not only to have control over process execution, but also over domain transition or authorization scheme.
[src:selinux-policy/type-enforcement] This is why it is best implemented as a kernel module, as is the case with SELinux.
[src:selinux-policy/type-enforcement] Using type enforcement is a way to implement the FLASK architecture.
[src:selinux-policy/type-enforcement] Using type enforcement, users may (as in Microsoft Active Directory) or may not (as in SELinux) be associated with a Kerberos realm, although the original type enforcement model implies so.
[src:selinux-policy/type-enforcement] It is always necessary to define a TE access matrix containing rules about clearance granted to a given security context, or subject's rights over objects according to an authorization scheme.
[src:selinux-policy/type-enforcement] Practically, type enforcement evaluates a set of rules from the source security context of a subject, against a set of rules from the target security context of the object.
[src:selinux-policy/type-enforcement] A clearance decision occurs depending on the TE access description (matrix).
[src:selinux-policy/type-enforcement] Then, DAC or other access control mechanisms (MLS / MCS, ...) apply.
[src:selinux-policy/type-enforcement] Type enforcement was introduced in the Secure Ada Target architecture in the late 1980s with a full implementation developed in the Logical Coprocessing Kernel (LOCK) system.
[src:selinux-policy/type-enforcement] The Sidewinder Internet Firewall was implemented on a custom version of Unix that incorporated type enforcement.
[src:selinux-policy/type-enforcement] A variant called *domain type enforcement* was developed in the Trusted MACH system.
[src:selinux-policy/type-enforcement] The original type enforcement model stated that labels should be attached to subject and object: a “domain label” for a subject and a “type label” for an object.
[src:selinux-policy/type-enforcement] This implementation mechanism was improved by the FLASK architecture, substituting complex structures and implicit relationship.
[src:selinux-policy/type-enforcement] Also, the original TE access matrix was extended to other structures: lattice-based, history-based, environment-based, policy logic...
[src:selinux-policy/type-enforcement] This is a matter of implementation of TE by the various operating systems.
[src:selinux-policy/type-enforcement] In SELinux, TE implementation does not internally distinguish TE-domain from TE-types.
[src:selinux-policy/type-enforcement] It should be considered a weakness of TE original model to specify detailed implementation aspects such as labels and matrix, especially using the terms “domain” and “types” which have other, more generic, widely accepted meanings.
